          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white dark:bg-[#111111] rounded-xl border border-[#ebebeb] dark:border-[#2e2e2e]
                    divide-y divide-[#ebebeb] dark:divide-[#2e2e2e]
                    shadow-[0_1px_1px_rgba(0,0,0,0.02),0_2px_2px_rgba(0,0,0,0.04)] overflow-hidden">

          <!-- Q1: What is spam? -->
          <details class="group">
            <summary class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer list-none
                            hover:bg-[#fafafa] dark:hover:bg-[#1a1a1a] transition-colors">
              <span class="text-[14px] font-medium text-[#171717] dark:text-[#ededed]">What is spam?</span>
              <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-[#888] dark:text-[#666] flex-shrink-0 transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180"
                   fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" aria-hidden="true">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
              </svg>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-[13px] text-[#4d4d4d] dark:text-[#a0a0a0] leading-relaxed space-y-2">
              <p>Spam refers to unsolicited bulk messages sent without the recipient's consent — typically for advertising, phishing, spreading malware, or fraud. Email spam alone accounts for nearly half of all global email traffic.</p>
              <p>Spam also appears as text messages (SMS spam), robocalls, social media messages, and comment spam on websites. Common signs include suspicious sender addresses, urgent language, too-good-to-be-true offers, requests for personal information, and links to unfamiliar domains.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <!-- Q2: How to block spam calls? -->
          <details class="group">
            <summary class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer list-none
                            hover:bg-[#fafafa] dark:hover:bg-[#1a1a1a] transition-colors">
              <span class="text-[14px] font-medium text-[#171717] dark:text-[#ededed]">How to block spam calls?</span>
              <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-[#888] dark:text-[#666] flex-shrink-0 transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180"
                   fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" aria-hidden="true">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
              </svg>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-[13px] text-[#4d4d4d] dark:text-[#a0a0a0] leading-relaxed">
              <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-1.5">
                <li>Register on your country's Do Not Call list — in the US, visit <span class="font-mono text-[12px]" translate="no">donotcall.gov</span>.</li>
                <li>Use your carrier's built-in call-screening service; most major carriers offer this free.</li>
                <li>Enable your phone's native protection: on Android, open Phone → Settings → Spam and Call Screen; on iPhone, go to Settings → Phone → Silence Unknown Callers.</li>
                <li>Install a third-party call-blocking app such as Hiya, Nomorobo, or Robokiller.</li>
                <li>Never press any keys in response to automated prompts — this confirms your number is active and increases the volume of calls you receive.</li>
              </ol>
            </div>
          </details>

          <!-- Q3: How to stop spam emails? -->
          <details class="group">
            <summary class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer list-none
                            hover:bg-[#fafafa] dark:hover:bg-[#1a1a1a] transition-colors">
              <span class="text-[14px] font-medium text-[#171717] dark:text-[#ededed]">How to stop spam emails?</span>
              <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-[#888] dark:text-[#666] flex-shrink-0 transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180"
                   fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" aria-hidden="true">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
              </svg>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-[13px] text-[#4d4d4d] dark:text-[#a0a0a0] leading-relaxed">
              <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-1.5">
                <li>Never share your primary email publicly — use a secondary or disposable address for sign-ups.</li>
                <li>Unsubscribe from legitimate mailing lists using the unsubscribe link at the bottom of emails.</li>
                <li>Mark unwanted messages as <em>Junk</em> or <em>Spam</em> to train your email client's filter.</li>
                <li>Use a provider with strong built-in filtering such as Gmail or Outlook.</li>
                <li>Enable two-factor authentication to prevent account takeovers that generate outbound spam.</li>
                <li>Never click links or download attachments in suspicious emails — doing so can subscribe you to more spam lists or install malware.</li>
              </ol>
            </div>
          </details>

          <!-- Q4: What is phishing? -->
          <details class="group">
            <summary class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer list-none
                            hover:bg-[#fafafa] dark:hover:bg-[#1a1a1a] transition-colors">
              <span class="text-[14px] font-medium text-[#171717] dark:text-[#ededed]">What is phishing?</span>
              <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-[#888] dark:text-[#666] flex-shrink-0 transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180"
                   fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" aria-hidden="true">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
              </svg>
            </summary>
            <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-[13px] text-[#4d4d4d] dark:text-[#a0a0a0] leading-relaxed space-y-2">
              <p>Phishing is a cyberattack in which criminals impersonate trusted organisations — banks, tech companies, or government agencies — to trick victims into revealing passwords, credit card numbers, or other sensitive data.</p>
              <p>Attacks arrive most commonly via email, but also through SMS (smishing) and phone calls (vishing). Warning signs include urgent or threatening language, generic greetings like "Dear Customer," misspelled domain names, requests to log in via a link, and unexpected attachments.</p>
              <p>To protect yourself: always verify the sender's address, hover over links before clicking to inspect the destination, and type website URLs directly into your browser rather than following email links.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

        </div>
